<title>FRANCE: French drinks shares fall on higher &quot;sin&quot; taxes.</title>
<headline>French drinks shares fall on higher &quot;sin&quot; taxes.</headline>
<dateline>PARIS 1996-09-06</dateline>
<text>
<p>Shares in French drinks companies fell on Friday after the government announced plans to raise &quot;sin taxes&quot; as part of its tax reform programme.</p>
<p>Finance Minister Jean Arthuis confirmed on Friday that taxes on alcohol and tobacco would be increased.</p>
<p>Shares in LVMH were down 0.74 percent at 0930 GMT and Remy Cointreau's stock was 0.5 percent lower. Shares in Pernod Ricard, which depends more heavily on its home market, were down 1.25 percent at 292.30.</p>
<p>&quot;They're poorly oriented after the announcement of higher taxes on alcohol,&quot; a broker said.</p>
<p>Tobacco group Seita was 0.9 percent lower at 197 francs.</p>
<p>-- Paris Newsroom, +33 1 4221 5452</p>
